{"title_page": "Haaltert", "text_new": "{{Infobox Belgium municipality\n|name=Haaltert\n|picture= Kerksken, straatzicht foto2 2011-10-02 15.14.JPG\n|picture-legend= Kerksken\n|map=MnpHaaltertLocation.png\n|map-legend=Location of Haaltert in East Flanders\n|arms=Blason ville be Haaltert.svg\n|flag=Flag of Haaltert.svg\n|region={{BE-REG-FLE}}\n|community={{BE-NL}}\n|province={{BE-PROV-OV}}\n|arrondissement=[[Arrondissement of Aalst|Aalst]]\n|nis=41024\n|pyramid-date=\n|0-19=\n|20-64=\n|65=\n|foreigners=\n|foreigners-date=\n|mayor= Roger Coppens (VLD)\n|majority=[[Flemish Liberals and Democrats|VLD]], [[sp.a]] \n|postal-codes=9450, 9451\n|telephone-area=053\n|web=[http://www.haaltert.be/ www.haaltert.be]\n|coordinates = {{coord|50|54|N|04|00|E|region:BE|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n'''Haaltert''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u0266a\u02d0lt\u0259rt}}) is a [[municipality]] located in the [[Belgium|Belgian]] province of [[East Flanders]] in the [[Denderstreek]]. The municipality comprises the towns of [[Denderhoutem]], Haaltert proper, [[Heldergem]] and [[Kerksken]]. On January 1, 2006, Haaltert had a total population of 17,255. The total area is 30.30&nbsp;km\u00b2 which gives a [[population density]] of 569 inhabitants per km\u00b2. The current mayor of Haaltert is Veerle Baeyens, from the N-VA.\n\nThere is a 205 hectare nature reserve [[Den Dotter]] in the sub-municipalities of [[Aaigem]] (municipality [[Erpe-Mere]]) and Heldergem (municipality Haaltert). Haaltert is crossed by the [[Molenbeek-Ter Erpenbeek]] creek in Heldergem, Kerksken, and Haaltert.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nImage:Haaltert, Sint Gorikskerk positie1 foto3 2011-10-02 15.32.JPG|Haaltert, church: de Sint Gorikskerk \nImage:Kerksken, kerk foto1 2011-10-02 15.11.JPG|Kerksken, church\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170904193653/http://www.haaltert.be/ Official website] {{in lang|nl}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Haaltert\n|North     = [[Aalst, Belgium|Aalst]]\n|East      = [[Denderleeuw]]\n|South     = [[Ninove]]\n|West      = [[Herzele]]\n|Northwest = [[Erpe-Mere]]\n}}\n{{Municipalities in East Flanders}}\n\n[[Category:Haaltert| ]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of East Flanders]]\n[[Category:Populated places in East Flanders]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Belgium]]\n\n\n{{EastFlanders-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Belgium municipality\n|name=Haaltert\n|picture= Kerksken, straatzicht foto2 2011-10-02 15.14.JPG\n|picture-legend= Kerksken\n|map=MnpHaaltertLocation.png\n|map-legend=Location of Haaltert in East Flanders\n|arms=Blason ville be Haaltert.svg\n|flag=Flag of Haaltert.svg\n|region={{BE-REG-FLE}}\n|community={{BE-NL}}\n|province={{BE-PROV-OV}}\n|arrondissement=[[Arrondissement of Aalst|Aalst]]\n|nis=41024\n|pyramid-date=\n|0-19=\n|20-64=\n|65=\n|foreigners=\n|foreigners-date=\n|mayor= Roger Coppens (VLD)\n|majority=[[Flemish Liberals and Democrats|VLD]], [[sp.a]] \n|postal-codes=9450, 9451\n|telephone-area=053\n|web=[http://www.haaltert.be/ www.haaltert.be]\n|coordinates = {{coord|50|54|N|04|00|E|region:BE|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n'''Haaltert''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u0266a\u02d0lt\u0259rt}}) is a [[municipality]] located in the [[Belgium|Belgian]] province of [[East Flanders]] in the [[Denderstreek]]. The municipality comprises the towns of [[Denderhoutem]], Haaltert proper, [[Heldergem]] and [[Kerksken]]. On January 1, 2006, Haaltert had a total population of 17,255. The total area is 30.30&nbsp;km\u00b2 which gives a [[population density]] of 569 inhabitants per km\u00b2. The current mayor of Haaltert is Veerle Baeyens, from the NVA.\n\nThere is a 205 hectare nature reserve [[Den Dotter]] in the sub-municipalities of [[Aaigem]] (municipality [[Erpe-Mere]]) and Heldergem (municipality Haaltert). Haaltert is crossed by the [[Molenbeek-Ter Erpenbeek]] creek in Heldergem, Kerksken, and Haaltert.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nImage:Haaltert, Sint Gorikskerk positie1 foto3 2011-10-02 15.32.JPG|Haaltert, church: de Sint Gorikskerk \nImage:Kerksken, kerk foto1 2011-10-02 15.11.JPG|Kerksken, church\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170904193653/http://www.haaltert.be/ Official website] {{in lang|nl}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Haaltert\n|North     = [[Aalst, Belgium|Aalst]]\n|East      = [[Denderleeuw]]\n|South     = [[Ninove]]\n|West      = [[Herzele]]\n|Northwest = [[Erpe-Mere]]\n}}\n{{Municipalities in East Flanders}}\n\n[[Category:Haaltert| ]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of East Flanders]]\n[[Category:Populated places in East Flanders]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Belgium]]\n\n\n{{EastFlanders-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bosser1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haaltert"}
{"title_page": "Vadu Izei", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Maramure\u0219 \n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Maramure\u0219 County\n|coordinates            = {{coord|47.8897|N|23.9311|E|source:kolossus-dewiki|display=it}}\n|name=Vadu Izei\n|image_map              = Vadu Izei jud Maramures.jpg\n}}\n'''Vadu Izei''' ({{lang-hu|Farkasr\u00e9v}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Maramure\u0219 County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of two villages, Vadu Izei and Valea Stejarului (''Diszn\u00f3pataka'').\n\n{{Maramure\u0219 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Maramure\u0219 County]]\n\n{{Maramure\u015f-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Maramure\u0219 \n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Maramure\u0219 County\n|coordinates            = {{coord|47.8897|N|23.9311|E|source:kolossus-dewiki|display=it}}\n|name=Vadu Izei\n|image_map              = Vadu Izei jud Maramures.jpg\n}}\n'''Vadu Izei''' ({{lang-hu|Farkasr\u00e9v}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Maramure\u0219 County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of two villages, Vadu Izei and Valea Stejarului (''Diszn\u00f3pataka'').\n\n{{Maramure\u015f County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Maramure\u0219 County]]\n\n{{Maramure\u015f-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: Maramure\u015f County \u2192 Maramure\u0219 County", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vadu_Izei"}
{"title_page": "Pitmiddle", "text_new": "{{infobox UK place \n|static_image_name=\n|static_image_width= \n|static_image_caption= \n|country= Scotland\n|region=\n|unitary_scotland= [[Perth and Kinross]]\n|lieutenancy_scotland = [[Perth and Kinross]]\n|constituency_scottish_parliament = \n|constituency_scottish_parliament1 =  \n|civil_parish=\n|shire_county= \n|official_name= \n|os_grid_reference =  NO 24419 29651 \n|coordinates = {{coord|56|27|11|N|3|13|35|W|display=inline}}\n|map_type = Scotland\n|post_town=PERTH\n|postcode_area= \n|postcode_district=  \n|dial_code=\n|constituency_westminster= }}\n\n'''Pitmiddle''' was a village in the [[Gowrie]] region of [[Perthshire]], Scotland. It is now deserted, the last resident having left in 1938. Its history dates back to the [[12th century]]. It is now a [[scheduled monument]].<ref name=tayl>[https://www.taylp.org/omeka/files/original/35/175/16037_1.31_TLP_Clay_Biggins_Vol._2_2018.03.23_sm.pdf Clay Building Survey] - Tay Landscape Partnership</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe earliest form of Pitmiddle's name was ''Petmeodhel'' (''pet'' being a [[Pict]]ish word meaning ''piece of land'', while the origin of ''meodhel'' is unknown).<ref name=psns/>\n\n==Geography==\nLocated {{convert|0.5|mi|km|abbr=off|0}} north of [[Kinnaird, Gowrie|Kinnaird]] in the centre of the parish, Pitmiddle \"was once a thriving hilltop community and home to several hundred people\",<ref name=courier>''[[The Courier (Dundee)|The Courier]]'', 11 April 2020, pp. 22 & 23</ref> but its remote location eventually led to its [[abandoned village|abandonment]].<ref name=courier/> The hills referenced are the Braes of the Carse, which reach heights of around {{convert|180|m|ft}}.<ref name=psns>[http://www.psns.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/PSNS-Pitmiddle-Village-and-Elcho-Nunnery-1988-complete-book.pdf \"Pitmiddle Village and Elcho Nunnery - Research and Excavation on Tayside\"] - Perthshire Society of Natural Science (1988)</ref>\n\nThe location is on a slope overlooking the [[River Tay]], but sheltered from the south by Guardswell Hill and to the north by Pitmiddle Hill, which rises to over {{convert|275|m|ft}}.<ref name=psns/>\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Pitmiddle_2.jpeg|thumb|right|Pitmiddle around the turn of the 20th century, looking west towards [[Knapp, Perthshire|Knapp]]<ref>[https://www.peakfinder.org/?lat=56.4531&lng=-3.2264&azi=266&zoom=4&ele=201&name=Pitmiddle Pitmiddle on PeakFinder]</ref>]] \n\nAlthough Pitmiddle was first called a [[toun]] in 1425,<ref name=psns/> the earliest reference to Pitmiddle is in a charter dating from 1172 to 1174. In it, [[William the Lion]] granted Ralph Rufus \"Kinnaird in its right divisions except ''Petmeodhel'' belonging to Richard my clerk\". This demonstrates that Pitmiddle and Kinnaird were originally [[royal land]]s. Pitmiddle belonged to the [[laird]] of [[Inchture|Inchmartine]]; Kinnaird to the laird of [[Fingask]]. Pitmiddle was held by the Inchmartines for around 150 years. The village itself was never a [[Barony (county division)|barony]], but was likely dealt with as a detached part of the barony of [[Longforgan]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nTenants paid ''cain'' and ''conveth''. Cain was originally a donation to a lord in recognition of his position. Conveth was a hospitality payment made to a lord on his annual visit to his estate. These were originally payment [[in kind]], in produce from the land.<ref name=psns/> Some tenants may have been [[free tenant|free]], but most were held in some degree of [[serfdom]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe Ogilvy family owned five-sixths of Inchmartine and Pitmiddle in the late [[15th century]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe village was not involved in the [[Jacobite risings]] of 1715 and 1745, but the neighbouring estate of Kinnaird was lost after 1715 due to its owner, Threipland of Fingask, being a supporter of the Jacobite movement.<ref name=psns/>\n\nAgricultural changes in the [[18th century]] affected the nature of the community, eventually leading to its abandonment.<ref name=psns/> By 1783, two more touns had been established on land belonging to Pitmiddle, effectively  depriving it of most of its farmland. These were Newtown (now Outfield) to the north and Bank (now Guardswell) to the south.<ref name=psns/>\n\nAfter the [[Scottish Reformation]], Kinnaird became a separate parish.<ref name=psns/>\n\nToday, hidden amongst farmland and woods, the only remnants of the community are a few crumbling walls and the wild [[redcurrant]] and [[gooseberry]] bushes that once grew in the residents' gardens.<ref name=courier/> A 2017 survey found the ruins of nine buildings.<ref name=tayl/>\n\n===Settlement and families===\nWilliam Thomassoun was living in Pitmiddle in the 15th century as a \"small but free tenant\". He had a son, Richard.<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn 1691, around 250 people lived in the village, along with the hamlet of Craigdallie, which was at the bottom of the hill.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nOn a 1783 map by James Stobie, Pitmiddle appeared as an irregularly shaped cluster of dwellings. The buildings would have been single-storied, made of [[wattle-and-daub]], roofed with turf or thatch \u2013 the latter made from reeds from the banks of the Tay. There would be a single room for living space, with one end cordoned-off for animals. An open hearth would have provided heat, possibly with a hole in the roof to extract smoke. Domestic rubbish would have been thrown onto a [[midden]] near the entrance. Attached to the hut was a yard where hens or pigs foraged and vegetables were grown. Enclosing the settlement was a ditch, beyond which was the arable land, and separated from it by the head [[dyke]] was the pasture.<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe main crops grown at Pitmeddle, per three [[17th century|17th-century]] rent rolls, were [[Bere (grain)|bere]] (a four-eared variety of barley) and oats. These also formed the basis of the peasants' diets. [[Wheat]] was later also grown.<ref name=psns/>\n\nPitmiddle is believe to have had a [[shieling]] on Blacklaw (Black Hill) to the north. By 1609, these had been turned into a sheep farm.<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn the [[16th century]], Androu Benbie (possibly Benvie) was living as a [[wright]]. Also, Edmund Jackson was fined ten [[shilling]]s for \"striking the common hird on the [[Sabbath]]\".<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn the 17th century, due to a greater survival in documentary evidence, more family names are known. These include: Anderson, Christal, Mores (possibly Morris or Moreis), Morton (possibly Mortoun), Millar, Blair, Mitchell, Whittet, Duncan, Paterson, Ogilvy, Young, Boug, Deucat (possibly Deugatt), Smyth, Christie, Robertson, Matthew, Thom, Gairdner (possibly Gardiner), Bowack (possibly Book, Boug or Boyok), Will, Hall, Muir (possibly Moor or Mure), Pirie (possibly Pierie), Martine and Lawson (possibly Lousone). In 1650, there were 19 tenants.<ref name=psns/>\n\n[[File:Pitmiddle_c._1900.jpg|thumb|right|Pitmiddle around 1900, looking north to Gask Hill.<ref>[https://www.peakfinder.org/?lat=56.4531&lng=-3.2264&azi=9&zoom=5&ele=201&binoazi=7.03&binoalt=-14.67&name=Pitmiddle Pitmiddle on PeakFinder]</ref> This view was used to create [https://imgur.com/a/cKtN3x9 a model of the settlement] that was on display at [[Perth Museum and Art Gallery]]]]\n\n[[File:Pitmiddle_sawmill.jpg|thumb|right|Employees of Pitmiddle's sawmill in March 1915]]\n\nEarly in the [[19th century]], the homes at Pitmiddle were rebuilt in stone, seemingly on the site of their timber predecessors. They were single storey and thatched. The floors were stone flagged and the fireplaces were built into the gables. The houses were divided into two rooms by box beds. The kitchen fireplace had hooks for kettles and pans. Ashes were kept back by a piece of iron. Around the fireplace was a fender, with a fender stool. The 1861 census showed that all households had two rooms with windows, except John Soutar's farmhouse, which had three. By 1891, there were three families each living in a cottage with three rooms with windows and two families with only one such room, the rest still having two such rooms. Attached to the houses were wooden sheds, [[byre]]s and small gardens. The village's water supply was sourced from three wells.<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe rebuilding of the village failed to halt Pitmiddle's demise. A once-thriving community of weavers, a blacksmith, two joiners, a tailor, a butcher and a public house<ref name=scotsman/> was now seeing young people leaving to work in the factories in nearby [[Dundee]] and [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nJust under one hundred people, living in 26 households, made up Pitmiddle's population in 1841.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nIn December 1896, ''[[The Dundee Courier]]'' sent two reporters to Pitmiddle (which had seven families living there at the time) to investigate its living conditions after reports of \"clearance-style\" conditions on the hill. The reporters visited Maidie Mitchell and her sister, \"two very old ladies,\" who had spent their entire lives in Pitmiddle.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nBy 1897, there were only sixteen inhabitants,<ref>Longforgan news article</ref> exactly half of what there had been six years earlier.<ref>[https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/perth-kinross/1035486/long-read-soon-there-will-be-nothing-left-the-sad-story-of-taysides-ghost-village/ \"Tayside's lost village\"] - ''The Courier''</ref>\n\nA [[sawmill]] was active from before 1915.<ref>[https://www.forestry-memories.org.uk/picture/number1104/ \"Pitmiddle Sawmill March 1915\"] - Forestry Memories, 11 April 2012</ref> On an [[Ordnance Survey]] map of 1861, a \"mill dam\" is shown southeast of the settlement, towards today's Guardswell Farm.<ref>[https://i0.wp.com/holeousia.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/pitmiddle-village-1861.jpg?ssl=1 Ordnance Survey map, 1861]</ref>\n\nFollowing the breakup of the Inchmartine estate in 1917, Pitmiddle was eventually bought by the White family and farmed from Outfield. In 1930 there were only two houses that were occupied. The final resident, James Gillies Jr., one of ten children  of [[stonemason]] James Sr. (1832\u20131920) and Margaret (1833\u20131908),<ref name=westmuir>[http://www.westmuir.org.uk/PDF%20Pages/Soldiering%20On.pdf \"\u2018Soldiering On\u2019 \u2026\u2026\u2026 and Magdalene\"] - Westmuir.org.uk</ref> left his home there for final time on 4 January, 1938. Winter storms had cancelled the sale of his farm.<ref name=courier/><ref name=psns/><ref name=scotsman>[https://www.scotsman.com/arts-and-culture/when-last-man-left-lost-village-pitmiddle-807807 \"When the last man left the lost village of Pitmiddle\"] - ''[[The Scotsman]]'', 12 September 2018</reF>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.psns.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/PSNS-Pitmiddle-Village-and-Elcho-Nunnery-1988-complete-book.pdf \"Pitmiddle Village and Elcho Nunnery - Research and Excavation on Tayside\"] - Perthshire Society of Natural Science (1988)\n*\"The lost village of Pitmiddle\" [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3g6MDFkv1EA part one], [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=979Ff6-nxxs part two] - Jagbetty, [[YouTube]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ms4tdyfuDxw \"Pitmiddle Village Revisited November 2014\"] - wattage2007, YouTube\n*[https://vimeo.com/225400714 \"Pitmiddle - the sun is still shining, long-shadowedly\"] - omphalos, [[Vimeo]]\n*[https://holeousia.com/2017/07/12/pitmiddle-village/ Pitmiddle village] - Hole Ousia\n*[https://www.forestry-memories.org.uk/picture/number1105 A second photograph of the workers at Pitmiddle's sawmill]\n\n{{Perth & Kinross Towns & Villages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pitmiddle}}\n[[Category:Villages in Perth and Kinross]]\n[[Category:Former villages in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scheduled monuments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Ruins in Perth and Kinross]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox UK place \n|static_image_name=\n|static_image_width= \n|static_image_caption= \n|country= Scotland\n|region=\n|unitary_scotland= [[Perth and Kinross]]\n|lieutenancy_scotland = [[Perth and Kinross]]\n|constituency_scottish_parliament = \n|constituency_scottish_parliament1 =  \n|civil_parish=\n|shire_county= \n|official_name= \n|os_grid_reference =  NO 24419 29651 \n|coordinates = {{coord|56|27|11|N|3|13|35|W|display=inline}}\n|map_type = Scotland\n|post_town=PERTH\n|postcode_area= \n|postcode_district=  \n|dial_code=\n|constituency_westminster= }}\n\n'''Pitmiddle''' was a village in the [[Gowrie]] region of [[Perthshire]], Scotland. It is now deserted, the last resident having left in 1938. Its history dates back to the [[12th century]]. It is now a [[scheduled monument]].<ref name=tayl>[https://www.taylp.org/omeka/files/original/35/175/16037_1.31_TLP_Clay_Biggins_Vol._2_2018.03.23_sm.pdf Clay Building Survey] - Tay Landscape Partnership</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe earliest form of Pitmiddle's name was ''Petmeodhel'' (''pet'' being a [[Pict]]ish word meaning ''piece of land'', while the origin of ''meodhel'' is unknown).<ref name=psns/>\n\n==Geography==\nLocated {{convert|0.5|mi|km|abbr=off|0}} north of [[Kinnaird, Gowrie|Kinnaird]] in the centre of the parish, Pitmiddle \"was once a thriving hilltop community and home to several hundred people\",<ref name=courier>''[[The Courier (Dundee)|The Courier]]'', 11 April 2020, pp. 22 & 23</ref> but its remote location eventually led to its [[abandoned village|abandonment]].<ref name=courier/> The hills referenced are the Braes of the Carse, which reach heights of around {{convert|180|m|ft}}.<ref name=psns>[http://www.psns.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/PSNS-Pitmiddle-Village-and-Elcho-Nunnery-1988-complete-book.pdf \"Pitmiddle Village and Elcho Nunnery - Research and Excavation on Tayside\"] - Perthshire Society of Natural Science (1988)</ref>\n\nThe location is on a slope overlooking the [[River Tay]], but sheltered from the south by Guardswell Hill and to the north by Pitmiddle Hill, which rises to over {{convert|275|m|ft}}.<ref name=psns/>\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Pitmiddle_2.jpeg|thumb|right|Pitmiddle around the turn of the 20th century, looking west towards [[Knapp, Perthshire|Knapp]]<ref>[https://www.peakfinder.org/?lat=56.4531&lng=-3.2264&azi=266&zoom=4&ele=201&name=Pitmiddle Pitmiddle on PeakFinder]</ref>]] \n\nAlthough Pitmiddle was first called a [[toun]] in 1425,<ref name=psns/> the earliest reference to Pitmiddle is in a charter dating from 1172 to 1174. In it, [[William the Lion]] granted Ralph Rufus \"Kinnaird in its right divisions except ''Petmeodhel'' belonging to Richard my clerk\". This demonstrates that Pitmiddle and Kinnaird were originally [[royal land]]s. Pitmiddle belonged to the [[laird]] of [[Inchture|Inchmartine]]; Kinnaird to the laird of [[Fingask]]. Pitmiddle was held by the Inchmartines for around 150 years. The village itself was never a [[Barony (county division)|barony]], but was likely dealt with as a detached part of the barony of [[Longforgan]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nTenants paid ''cain'' and ''conveth''. Cain was originally a donation to a lord in recognition of his position. Conveth was a hospitality payment made to a lord on his annual visit to his estate. These were originally payment [[in kind]], in produce from the land.<ref name=psns/> Some tenants may have been [[free tenant|free]], but most were held in some degree of [[serfdom]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe Ogilvy family owned five-sixths of Inchmartine and Pitmiddle in the late [[15th century]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe village was not involved in the [[Jacobite risings]] of 1715 and 1745, but the neighbouring estate of Kinnaird was lost after 1715 due to its owner, Threipland of Fingask, being a supporter of the Jacobite movement.<ref name=psns/>\n\nAgricultural changes in the [[18th century]] affected the nature of the community, eventually leading to its abandonment.<ref name=psns/> By 1783, two more touns had been established on land belonging to Pitmiddle, effectively  depriving it of most of its farmland. These were Newtown (now Outfield) to the north and Bank (now Guardswell) to the south.<ref name=psns/>\n\nAfter the [[Scottish Reformation]], Kinnaird became a separate parish.<ref name=psns/>\n\nToday, hidden amongst farmland and woods, the only remnants of the community are a few crumbling walls and the wild [[redcurrant]] and [[gooseberry]] bushes that once grew in the residents' gardens.<ref name=courier/> A 2017 survey found the ruins of nine buildings.<ref name=tayl/>\n\n===Settlement and families===\nWilliam Thomassoun was living in Pitmiddle in the 15th century as a \"small but free tenant\". He had a son, Richard.<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn 1691, around 250 people lived in the village, along with the hamlet of Craigdallie, which was at the bottom of the hill.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nOn a 1783 map by James Stobie, Pitmiddle appeared as an irregularly shaped cluster of dwellings. The buildings would have been single-storied, made of [[wattle-and-daub]], roofed with turf or thatch \u2013 the latter made from reeds from the banks of the Tay. There would be a single room for living space, with one end cordoned-off for animals. An open hearth would have provided heat, possibly with a hole in the roof to extract smoke. Domestic rubbish would have been thrown onto a [[midden]] near the entrance. Attached to the hut was a yard where hens or pigs foraged and vegetables were grown. Enclosing the settlement was a ditch, beyond which was the arable land, and separated from it by the head [[dyke]] was the pasture.<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe main crops grown at Pitmeddle, per three [[17th century|17th-century]] rent rolls, were [[Bere (grain)|bere]] (a four-eared variety of barley) and oats. These also formed the basis of the peasants' diets. [[Wheat]] was later also grown.<ref name=psns/>\n\nPitmiddle is believe to have had a [[shieling]] on Blacklaw (Black Hill) to the north. By 1609, these had been turned into a sheep farm.<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn the [[16th century]], Androu Benbie (possibly Benvie) was living as a [[wright]]. Also, Edmund Jackson was fined ten [[shilling]]s for \"striking the common hird on the [[Sabbath]]\".<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn the 17th century, due to a greater survival in documentary evidence, more family names are known. These include: Anderson, Christal, Mores (possibly Morris or Moreis), Morton (possibly Mortoun), Millar, Blair, Mitchell, Whittet, Duncan, Paterson, Ogilvy, Young, Boug, Deucat (possibly Deugatt), Smyth, Christie, Robertson, Matthew, Thom, Gairdner (possibly Gardiner), Bowack (possibly Book, Boug or Boyok), Will, Hall, Muir (possibly Moor or Mure), Pirie (possibly Pierie), Martine and Lawson (possibly Lousone). In 1650, there were 19 tenants.<ref name=psns/>\n\n[[File:Pitmiddle_c._1900.jpg|thumb|right|Pitmiddle around 1900, looking north to Gask Hill.<ref>[https://www.peakfinder.org/?lat=56.4531&lng=-3.2264&azi=9&zoom=5&ele=201&binoazi=7.03&binoalt=-14.67&name=Pitmiddle Pitmiddle at PeakFinder]</ref> This view was used to create [https://imgur.com/a/cKtN3x9 a model of the settlement] that was on display at [[Perth Museum and Art Gallery]]]]\n\n[[File:Pitmiddle_sawmill.jpg|thumb|right|Employees of Pitmiddle's sawmill in March 1915]]\n\nEarly in the [[19th century]], the homes at Pitmiddle were rebuilt in stone, seemingly on the site of their timber predecessors. They were single storey and thatched. The floors were stone flagged and the fireplaces were built into the gables. The houses were divided into two rooms by box beds. The kitchen fireplace had hooks for kettles and pans. Ashes were kept back by a piece of iron. Around the fireplace was a fender, with a fender stool. The 1861 census showed that all households had two rooms with windows, except John Soutar's farmhouse, which had three. By 1891, there were three families each living in a cottage with three rooms with windows and two families with only one such room, the rest still having two such rooms. Attached to the houses were wooden sheds, [[byre]]s and small gardens. The village's water supply was sourced from three wells.<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe rebuilding of the village failed to halt Pitmiddle's demise. A once-thriving community of weavers, a blacksmith, two joiners, a tailor, a butcher and a public house<ref name=scotsman/> was now seeing young people leaving to work in the factories in nearby [[Dundee]] and [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nJust under one hundred people, living in 26 households, made up Pitmiddle's population in 1841.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nIn December 1896, ''[[The Dundee Courier]]'' sent two reporters to Pitmiddle (which had seven families living there at the time) to investigate its living conditions after reports of \"clearance-style\" conditions on the hill. The reporters visited Maidie Mitchell and her sister, \"two very old ladies,\" who had spent their entire lives in Pitmiddle.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nBy 1897, there were only sixteen inhabitants,<ref>Longforgan news article</ref> exactly half of what there had been six years earlier.<ref>[https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/perth-kinross/1035486/long-read-soon-there-will-be-nothing-left-the-sad-story-of-taysides-ghost-village/ \"Tayside's lost village\"] - ''The Courier''</ref>\n\nA [[sawmill]] was active from before 1915.<ref>[https://www.forestry-memories.org.uk/picture/number1104/ \"Pitmiddle Sawmill March 1915\"] - Forestry Memories, 11 April 2012</ref> On an [[Ordnance Survey]] map of 1861, a \"mill dam\" is shown southeast of the settlement, towards today's Guardswell Farm.<ref>[https://i0.wp.com/holeousia.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/pitmiddle-village-1861.jpg?ssl=1 Ordnance Survey map, 1861]</ref>\n\nFollowing the breakup of the Inchmartine estate in 1917, Pitmiddle was eventually bought by the White family and farmed from Outfield. In 1930 there were only two houses that were occupied. The final resident, James Gillies Jr., one of ten children  of [[stonemason]] James Sr. (1832\u20131920) and Margaret (1833\u20131908),<ref name=westmuir>[http://www.westmuir.org.uk/PDF%20Pages/Soldiering%20On.pdf \"\u2018Soldiering On\u2019 \u2026\u2026\u2026 and Magdalene\"] - Westmuir.org.uk</ref> left his home there for final time on 4 January, 1938. Winter storms had cancelled the sale of his farm.<ref name=courier/><ref name=psns/><ref name=scotsman>[https://www.scotsman.com/arts-and-culture/when-last-man-left-lost-village-pitmiddle-807807 \"When the last man left the lost village of Pitmiddle\"] - ''[[The Scotsman]]'', 12 September 2018</reF>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.psns.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/PSNS-Pitmiddle-Village-and-Elcho-Nunnery-1988-complete-book.pdf \"Pitmiddle Village and Elcho Nunnery - Research and Excavation on Tayside\"] - Perthshire Society of Natural Science (1988)\n*\"The lost village of Pitmiddle\" [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3g6MDFkv1EA part one], [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=979Ff6-nxxs part two] - Jagbetty, [[YouTube]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ms4tdyfuDxw \"Pitmiddle Village Revisited November 2014\"] - wattage2007, YouTube\n*[https://vimeo.com/225400714 \"Pitmiddle - the sun is still shining, long-shadowedly\"] - omphalos, [[Vimeo]]\n*[https://holeousia.com/2017/07/12/pitmiddle-village/ Pitmiddle village] - Hole Ousia\n*[https://www.forestry-memories.org.uk/picture/number1105 A second photograph of the workers at Pitmiddle's sawmill]\n\n{{Perth & Kinross Towns & Villages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pitmiddle}}\n[[Category:Villages in Perth and Kinross]]\n[[Category:Former villages in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scheduled monuments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Ruins in Perth and Kinross]]\n", "name_user": "Seasider53", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pitmiddle"}
{"title_page": "G\u00f6lgelikonak", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Eruh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Coord|37|46|19|N|42|07|49|E|display=title}}\n{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|official_name = G\u00f6lgelikonak\n|settlement_type = \n|timezone= [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|map_caption =Location of G\u00f6lgelikonak within Turkey.\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name = Turkey\n|subdivision_type1=[[Regions of Turkey|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Southeastern Anatolia Region]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Provinces of Turkey|Province]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Siirt Province]]\n|subdivision_type3=[[Districts of Turkey|District]]\n|subdivision_name3 = [[Eruh]]\n|population_total= 4,863\n|population_date= 2000 \n|pushpin_map =Turkey\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of G\u00f6lgelikonak\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|coordinates      = {{coord|37|46|19|N|42|07|49|E|region:TR|display=inline}}\n|elevation_m =1008\n}}\n\n'''G\u00f6lgelikonak''' ({{lang-ku|Hil\u00ealok}}) is a village in the [[Eruh]] district of the [[Siirt Province]] in [[Turkey]], with a population of about 4,800. It is also known as H\u00fcl\u00fcl\u00fck, Hileyluk, Hililuk, Hilil\u00fck, Hileyl\u00fck and Hululuk.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golgelikonak}}\n[[Category:Villages in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Siirt Province]]\n\n\n{{Siirt-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sems\u00fbr\u00ee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2190Redirected page toEruh", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=G%C3%B6lgelikonak&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Benazir Income Support Programme", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Benazir Income Support Programme\n| pronounce           = \n| native_name  sima       = \u0628\u06cc\u0646\u0638\u06cc\u0631 \u0627\u0646\u06a9\u0645 \u0633\u067e\u0648\u0631\u0679 \u067e\u0631\u0648\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645\n| native_name_lang    = ur\n| named_after         = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| logo                = \n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| map                 = \n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map2                = \n| map2_size           = \n| map2_alt            = \n| map2_caption        = \n| abbreviation        = BISP \n| motto               = \n| predecessor         = \n| merged              = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = {{start date and age|df=yes|2008|07|}} \n| founder             = \n| focus =  Health, Education, Social Protection, Reduce poverty , Enhance financial capacity of poor people \n| founding_location   = \n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger              = \n| type                = [[Social safety net]]\n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status              = \n| purpose             = \n| headquarters        = F-Block, [[ Pakistan Secretariat]], [[Islamabad]], [[Pakistan]]\n| location            = \n| coords              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} -->\n| region              = \n| services            = \n| products            = \n| methods             = [[Donations]], [[Scholarship]]\n| fields              = \n| membership          = \n| membership_year     = \n| language            = 1988\n| owner               = [[Government of Pakistan]]\n| sec_gen             = \n| leader_title        =  Chairperson of BISP \n| leader_name   eidmuhammad      = Dr. [[Sania Nishtar]] <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/387574-dr-sania-nishtar-appointed-bisp-chairman|title=Dr Sania Nishtar appointed BISP chairperson|date=30 October 2018 |newspaper=The News|location=Pakistan|access-date=30 October 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n| leader_title2       = \n| leader_name2        = \n| leader_title3       = \n| leader_name3        = \n| leader_title4       = \n| leader_name4        = \n| board_of_directors  = \n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        = \n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = [[Government of Pakistan]]\n| budget              = [[US$]] 1.15 Billion <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bisp.gov.pk/|title=Benazir Income Support Programme buget|website=bisp.gov.pk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-30}}</ref>\n| budget_year         = \n| revenue             = \n| revenue_year        = \n| disbursements       = \n| expenses            = \n| expenses_year       = \n| endowment           = \n| endowment_year      = \n| staff               = \n| num_employees =      2,381 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bisp.gov.pk/|title=Benazir Income Support Programme|website=bisp.gov.pk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-30}}</ref> \n| staff_year          = \n| volunteers          = \n| volunteers_year     = \n| website             = {{URL|http://bisp.gov.pk/}}\n| remarks             = \n| formerly            = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n[[File:Benazir Bhutto.jpg|thumb|The program is named after Prime Minister [[Benazir Bhutto]].]]\nThe '''Benazir Income Support Programme''' (BISP) is a federal [[unconditional cash transfer]] [[poverty reduction]] program in [[Pakistan]]. Launched in July 2008, it is the largest single [[social safety net]] program in the country with nearly Rs. 90 billion ([[$]]900 million) distributed to 5.4 million beneficiaries in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/173127-DFID-lauds-BISP-performance-by-giving-it-overall-A-rating|title=DFID lauds BISP performance by giving it overall \u2018A\u2019 rating|website=www.thenews.com.pk|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department for International Development]] of the [[Government of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] is the largest foreign backer of the program, providing [[$]]244 million (or 27%) of the total funds in 2016 with the [[Government of Pakistan|Pakistani Government]] providing the rest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1292459/aid-watchdog-defends-uk-funding-benazir-income-support-programme/|title=Aid watchdog defends UK funding of Benazir Income Support Programme - The Express Tribune|date=2017-01-12|newspaper=The Express Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/03/pakistan-cash-transfers-defended-mp-says-aid-programme-amounts/|title=Pakistan cash transfers defended as MP says aid programme amounts to 'exporting the dole'|newspaper=The Telegraph|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, the program distributes Rs.19,338 (or approx. [[$]]195) per annum distributed per month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1287466|title=BISP stipend increased|date=2016-10-02|newspaper=DAWN.COM|access-date=2017-01-13}}</ref> The stipend is linked to the [[Consumer price index|Consumer Price Index]] and is paid through a [[smart card]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.app.com.pk/pml-n-govt-increases-stipend-for-bisp-beneficiaries/|title=PML-N Govt increases stipend for BISP beneficiaries|last=Uploader|date=2016-10-01|newspaper=Associate Press Of Pakistan|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-13}}</ref> For now, Dr Sania Nishtar is Chairman of BISP in regime of PTI governance. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/461247-bisp-set-to-speedily-undertake-measures-to-tackle-poverty-sania|title=BISP set to speedily undertake measures to tackle poverty: Sania|date=2019-04-22|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Benazir Income Support Programme was established in 2008 by [[Yousaf Raza Gillani]] who took the advice of President Asif Ali Zardari.  The program's name is a tribute to former Prime Minister and widow of President Zardari, [[Benazir Bhutto]], who was assassinated in 2007.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}\n\nSince 2005, the purchasing power of many Pakistani families has been eroded by high inflation and the increasing cost of food and oil.  BISP arose against this backdrop as a means to address reductions in purchasing power.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}  Along with the economic development aims of the program, BISP also seeks to empower women by presenting cash transfers directly to female members of households.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\nBISP is currently the largest aid program in Pakistan and the government's third largest budgetary allocation.  BISP spending accounts for 0.3% of Pakistan's GDP.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}\n\nIn the 2008\u20132009 fiscal year, more than 3 million Pakistani families received cash transfers through BISP; this figure accounts for 1.5% of the general population{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}} and 10% of the population below the poverty level.  For the 2009\u20132010 fiscal year, the program was expanded to cover 5 million low-income families.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}  At the program's start in 2008, the Pakistani government allocated RS 34&nbsp;billion, or $425&nbsp;million, for BISP; the allocation doubled to RS 70&nbsp;billion, or $875&nbsp;million in the following year.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\nThe Benazir Income Support Programme is planning to launch a new initiative that encourages [[human capital]] development through a [[conditional cash transfer]].  The Waseela-e-Taleem initiative will condition cash payments on primary school enrolment for the children of eligible families.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}} On 18 June 2017, BISP launched an e-commerce platform for its beneficiaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/millennialpk/pakistans-new-plan-to-eradicate-poverty-use-embroidery-4a14b5cdfac0|title=Pakistan\u2019s New Plan to Eradicate Poverty: Use Embroidery|last=Wani|first=Shahrukh|date=2017-06-18|website=Medium|access-date=2017-06-24}}</ref>\n\n==Program structure==\nThe Benazir Income Support Programme has been implemented in the provinces of [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Sindh]], [[Baluchistan]], and [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtonnkhwa]].  The program also operates in the federally administered regions of [[Azad Jammu and Kashmir]], and the Islamabad Capital Territory.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\nIn its first year of operation, recipients of BISP cash transfers were identified and selected by Parliamentarians through a process of recommendation.  Each Parliamentarian received 8,000 forms to distribute throughout his or her constituency.  Selected individuals underwent an eligibility verification process through the National Database and Registration Authority.  A final list of eligible families was generated and sent to the postal service.  Funds were disbursed from the Treasury directly to the postal service and then delivered to the female head of eligible households.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}\n\nIn April 2009, the process for identifying a selecting eligible families through Parliamentarian recommendation was ended.  The identification process has been reformed and now uses a Poverty Scorecard.  Through the Poverty Scorecard, families are identified through a proxy means test.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}  The Poverty Scorecard has been approved by the World Bank and requires families to answer 13 questions regarding assets and expenses in a survey.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}  The poverty survey has been tested in 16 districts and will be distributed nationwide.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\nInternal monitoring systems are being developed to track deliveries and payment amounts to eligible families.  Another mechanism to address corruption and political favouritism is being considered that would allow a neutral third party access to the list of eligible families to verify eligibility.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}\n\nRecently, BISP has expanded to include several special initiatives.  The Waseela-e-Haq program empowers women through the provision of small loans.  A vocation training program, Waseela-e-Rozgar, offers members of eligible families up to 1 year of professional training.  The Waseela-e-Sehat program provides financial assistance specifically for obtaining basic health care.  BISP will launch its first program that conditions cash payments on schooling. The Waseela-e-Taleem initiative will require families receiving cash payments to enroll children between the ages of 5 to 12 to enroll in primary education.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\nBISP also provides cash payments for emergency relief efforts.  These payments are similar to the payments received by low-income families but are distributed to families affected by terrorism, war, and natural disasters such as earthquakes.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\n==Eligibility==\nTo be eligible for cash payments under BISP, families must earn less than RS 6,000 per month; equivalent to $67.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}  Further eligibility requirements stipulate that:\n*Families must have a female applicant holding a valid ID card\n*An individual applicant must be a widowed or divorced female without male family members\n*Eligible families include those with physically or mentally disabled individuals\n\nFamilies deemed ineligible for cash payments through BISP include those with:{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}\n*Members employed by the Pakistani government, army, or any other government-affiliated agency\n*Members drawing a pension or receiving post-retirement benefits from the government\n*Family members owning more than 3 acres of farmland or more than 80 square yards of residential land\n*Members receiving income from other sources\n*Members holding a machine readable passport\n*Members with a National Identity Card for Overseas citizens\n*Members with a bank account excluding microfinance banks and those catering to low-inc\nome families\n\n==Benefits==\nEligible families receive cash payments of 4834 quarterly.  This amount increases the purchasing power for families earning approximately RS 5,000 each month by 20%.  Most low-income families spend 50\u201370% of total income on food alone.  According to BISP, the cash payment of RS 3,000 every two months, or RS 1,500 each month, will allow a family of 5\u20136 to purchase 20\u201325 days worth of flour.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}\n\n==Criticism==\nSince the program's inception, critics have pointed out several overall flaws in the Benazir Income Support Program design.  Some claim that the amount of RS 3000 bi-monthly, or RS 1,500 per month, is not enough to move impoverished families above the poverty line as this would require RS 2,550 per month.  Another major flaw with BISP is its lack of conditionality.  Conditional cash transfer programs in Latin America have experienced greater degrees of success because recipient families must meet certain requirements before receiving a cash payment.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}  These programs build human capital through requiring recipients to enroll their children in primary education, participate in health and nutrition seminars, and visit health care providers.{{Sfn|Rawlings-Rubio 2003}}  Apart from the Waseela-e-Taleem initiative, cash payments do not require recipients to meet particular obligations in return for cash payments.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n \nThere have also been accusations of corruption and political favouritism.  By some estimates, only 50\u201360 percent of beneficiaries actually receive cash payments from BISP. The previous method of identifying families through the recommendation of Parliamentarians was flawed.  Many have claimed that Parliamentarians simply recommended their own family and friends to receive cash payments.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}  It has been pointed out that there is a disproportionate number of families receiving BISP aid in geographic areas where the ruling Pakistan People's Party dominates.  For example, in the Prime Minister's hometown of Multan, there is twice the number of people receiving BISP payments than in Lahore, the opposition party's stronghold.  Punjab, another area where opposition parties dominate, has the lowest ratio of eligible families\u20141,974 for every 100,000 people; versus 6,829 families for every 100,000 people in Sindh, the ruling party's stronghold.{{Sfn|Ghauri 2012}}  Beneficiaries have also complained that the postal service charges an additional RS 100 to RS 200 for each delivery of payment.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}\n\nOther critics have argued that as the Benazir Income Support Programme makes up a substantial portion of the Pakistani government's budget, impact evaluations should be conducted to evaluate the benefits and actual need for the program.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}\n\n==List of Chairpersons of Benazir Income Support Program==\n{| class=\"wikitable\n|-\n!align=center|Name of Chairperson\n!align=center|Entered Office\n!align=center|Left Office\n|-\n|[[Farzana Raja]]\n|July 2008\n|March 2013\n|-\n|Vacant\n|March 2013\n|November 2013\n|-\n|[[Enver Baig]]\n|November 2013\n|November 2014\n|-\n|Vacant\n|November 2014\n|February 2015\n|-\n|[[Marvi Memon]]\n|February 2015\n|June 2018\n|-\n|Vacant\n|June 2018\n|October 2018\n|-\n|[[Sania Nishtar]]\n|October 2018\n|Present\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n<!--- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. --->\n* {{Cite web |title=Benazir Income Support Programme |year=2011 |url=http://www.bisp.gov.pk/ |ref={{SfnRef|Benazir Income Support Programme}} }}\n* {{Cite web |last=Ghauri |first=Irfan |date=4 February 2012 |title=Benazir Income Support Programme: Does the Cash Flow to Blue-Eyed Voters? |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/331740/benazir-income-support-programme-does-the-cash-flow-to-blue-eyed-voters/ |ref={{SfnRef|Ghauri 2012}} |display-authors=etal}}\n* {{Cite web |last1=Handayani |first1=Sri Wening |last2=Burkley |first2=Clifford |year=2009 |title=Social Assistance and Conditional Cash Transfers: The Proceedings of the Regional Workshop. |url=http://www.adb.org/publications/social-assistance-and-conditional-cash-transfers-proceedings-regional-workshop |ref={{SfnRef|Handayani-Burkley 2009}} }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Rawlings |first1=Laura B |last2=Rubio |first2=Gloria M. |year=2003 |title=Evaluating the Impact of Conditional Cash Transfer Programs: Lessons from Latin America |ref={{SfnRef|Rawlings-Rubio 2003}} }}\n* {{Cite web |last=Shahzad |first=Farakh |date=25 June 2011 |title=BISP\u2014A Commitment Falling Short \n|url=http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2011/06/25/news/profit/bisp-a-commitment-falling-short/ |ref={{SfnRef|Shahzad 2011}} }}\n* {{Cite web |last=Saddam |first=Khan |date=28 Sep 2017 |title=BISP\n|url=http://www.pakistanblogger.com/bisp-tracking-by-cnic/ |ref={{SfnRef|Shahzad 2011}} }}\n* {{Cite web |last=Saddam |first=Hassan |date=30 Oct 2019 |title=BISP - Dr Sania Nishtar is Chairman in regime of PTI governance.\n|url=http://www.bisp.com.pk |ref={{SfnRef|Shahzad 2011}} }}\n\n[[Category:Welfare in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Government of Yousaf Raza Gillani]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Benazir Bhutto]]\n[[Category:2008 introductions]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Social programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Benazir Income Support Programme\n| pronounce           = \n| native_name         = \u0628\u06cc\u0646\u0638\u06cc\u0631 \u0627\u0646\u06a9\u0645 \u0633\u067e\u0648\u0631\u0679 \u067e\u0631\u0648\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645\n| native_name_lang    = ur\n| named_after         = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| logo                = \n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| map                 = \n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map2                = \n| map2_size           = \n| map2_alt            = \n| map2_caption        = \n| abbreviation        = BISP \n| motto               = \n| predecessor         = \n| merged              = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = {{start date and age|df=yes|2008|07|}} \n| founder             = \n| focus =  Health, Education, Social Protection, Reduce poverty , Enhance financial capacity of poor people \n| founding_location   = \n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger              = \n| type                = [[Social safety net]]\n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status              = \n| purpose             = \n| headquarters        = F-Block, [[ Pakistan Secretariat]], [[Islamabad]], [[Pakistan]]\n| location            = \n| coords              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} -->\n| region              = \n| services            = \n| products            = \n| methods             = [[Donations]], [[Scholarship]]\n| fields              = \n| membership          = \n| membership_year     = \n| language            = \n| owner               = [[Government of Pakistan]]\n| sec_gen             = \n| leader_title        =  Chairperson of BISP \n| leader_name         = Dr. [[Sania Nishtar]] <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/387574-dr-sania-nishtar-appointed-bisp-chairman|title=Dr Sania Nishtar appointed BISP chairperson|date=30 October 2018 |newspaper=The News|location=Pakistan|access-date=30 October 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n| leader_title2       = \n| leader_name2        = \n| leader_title3       = \n| leader_name3        = \n| leader_title4       = \n| leader_name4        = \n| board_of_directors  = \n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        = \n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = [[Government of Pakistan]]\n| budget              = [[US$]] 1.15 Billion <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bisp.gov.pk/|title=Benazir Income Support Programme buget|website=bisp.gov.pk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-30}}</ref>\n| budget_year         = \n| revenue             = \n| revenue_year        = \n| disbursements       = \n| expenses            = \n| expenses_year       = \n| endowment           = \n| endowment_year      = \n| staff               = \n| num_employees =      2,381 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bisp.gov.pk/|title=Benazir Income Support Programme|website=bisp.gov.pk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-30}}</ref> \n| staff_year          = \n| volunteers          = \n| volunteers_year     = \n| website             = {{URL|http://bisp.gov.pk/}}\n| remarks             = \n| formerly            = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n[[File:Benazir Bhutto.jpg|thumb|The program is named after Prime Minister [[Benazir Bhutto]].]]\nThe '''Benazir Income Support Programme''' (BISP) is a federal [[unconditional cash transfer]] [[poverty reduction]] program in [[Pakistan]]. Launched in July 2008, it is the largest single [[social safety net]] program in the country with nearly Rs. 90 billion ([[$]]900 million) distributed to 5.4 million beneficiaries in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/173127-DFID-lauds-BISP-performance-by-giving-it-overall-A-rating|title=DFID lauds BISP performance by giving it overall \u2018A\u2019 rating|website=www.thenews.com.pk|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department for International Development]] of the [[Government of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] is the largest foreign backer of the program, providing [[$]]244 million (or 27%) of the total funds in 2016 with the [[Government of Pakistan|Pakistani Government]] providing the rest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1292459/aid-watchdog-defends-uk-funding-benazir-income-support-programme/|title=Aid watchdog defends UK funding of Benazir Income Support Programme - The Express Tribune|date=2017-01-12|newspaper=The Express Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/03/pakistan-cash-transfers-defended-mp-says-aid-programme-amounts/|title=Pakistan cash transfers defended as MP says aid programme amounts to 'exporting the dole'|newspaper=The Telegraph|access-date=2017-01-12}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, the program distributes Rs.19,338 (or approx. [[$]]195) per annum distributed per month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1287466|title=BISP stipend increased|date=2016-10-02|newspaper=DAWN.COM|access-date=2017-01-13}}</ref> The stipend is linked to the [[Consumer price index|Consumer Price Index]] and is paid through a [[smart card]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.app.com.pk/pml-n-govt-increases-stipend-for-bisp-beneficiaries/|title=PML-N Govt increases stipend for BISP beneficiaries|last=Uploader|date=2016-10-01|newspaper=Associate Press Of Pakistan|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-13}}</ref> For now, Dr Sania Nishtar is Chairman of BISP in regime of PTI governance. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/461247-bisp-set-to-speedily-undertake-measures-to-tackle-poverty-sania|title=BISP set to speedily undertake measures to tackle poverty: Sania|date=2019-04-22|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Benazir Income Support Programme was established in 2008 by [[Yousaf Raza Gillani]] who took the advice of President Asif Ali Zardari.  The program's name is a tribute to former Prime Minister and widow of President Zardari, [[Benazir Bhutto]], who was assassinated in 2007.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}\n\nSince 2005, the purchasing power of many Pakistani families has been eroded by high inflation and the increasing cost of food and oil.  BISP arose against this backdrop as a means to address reductions in purchasing power.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}  Along with the economic development aims of the program, BISP also seeks to empower women by presenting cash transfers directly to female members of households.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\nBISP is currently the largest aid program in Pakistan and the government's third largest budgetary allocation.  BISP spending accounts for 0.3% of Pakistan's GDP.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}\n\nIn the 2008\u20132009 fiscal year, more than 3 million Pakistani families received cash transfers through BISP; this figure accounts for 1.5% of the general population{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}} and 10% of the population below the poverty level.  For the 2009\u20132010 fiscal year, the program was expanded to cover 5 million low-income families.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}  At the program's start in 2008, the Pakistani government allocated RS 34&nbsp;billion, or $425&nbsp;million, for BISP; the allocation doubled to RS 70&nbsp;billion, or $875&nbsp;million in the following year.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\nThe Benazir Income Support Programme is planning to launch a new initiative that encourages [[human capital]] development through a [[conditional cash transfer]].  The Waseela-e-Taleem initiative will condition cash payments on primary school enrolment for the children of eligible families.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}} On 18 June 2017, BISP launched an e-commerce platform for its beneficiaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/millennialpk/pakistans-new-plan-to-eradicate-poverty-use-embroidery-4a14b5cdfac0|title=Pakistan\u2019s New Plan to Eradicate Poverty: Use Embroidery|last=Wani|first=Shahrukh|date=2017-06-18|website=Medium|access-date=2017-06-24}}</ref>\n\n==Program structure==\nThe Benazir Income Support Programme has been implemented in the provinces of [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Sindh]], [[Baluchistan]], and [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtonnkhwa]].  The program also operates in the federally administered regions of [[Azad Jammu and Kashmir]], and the Islamabad Capital Territory.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\nIn its first year of operation, recipients of BISP cash transfers were identified and selected by Parliamentarians through a process of recommendation.  Each Parliamentarian received 8,000 forms to distribute throughout his or her constituency.  Selected individuals underwent an eligibility verification process through the National Database and Registration Authority.  A final list of eligible families was generated and sent to the postal service.  Funds were disbursed from the Treasury directly to the postal service and then delivered to the female head of eligible households.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}\n\nIn April 2009, the process for identifying a selecting eligible families through Parliamentarian recommendation was ended.  The identification process has been reformed and now uses a Poverty Scorecard.  Through the Poverty Scorecard, families are identified through a proxy means test.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}  The Poverty Scorecard has been approved by the World Bank and requires families to answer 13 questions regarding assets and expenses in a survey.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}  The poverty survey has been tested in 16 districts and will be distributed nationwide.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\nInternal monitoring systems are being developed to track deliveries and payment amounts to eligible families.  Another mechanism to address corruption and political favouritism is being considered that would allow a neutral third party access to the list of eligible families to verify eligibility.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}\n\nRecently, BISP has expanded to include several special initiatives.  The Waseela-e-Haq program empowers women through the provision of small loans.  A vocation training program, Waseela-e-Rozgar, offers members of eligible families up to 1 year of professional training.  The Waseela-e-Sehat program provides financial assistance specifically for obtaining basic health care.  BISP will launch its first program that conditions cash payments on schooling. The Waseela-e-Taleem initiative will require families receiving cash payments to enroll children between the ages of 5 to 12 to enroll in primary education.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\nBISP also provides cash payments for emergency relief efforts.  These payments are similar to the payments received by low-income families but are distributed to families affected by terrorism, war, and natural disasters such as earthquakes.{{Sfn|Benazir Income Support Programme}}\n\n==Eligibility==\nTo be eligible for cash payments under BISP, families must earn less than RS 6,000 per month; equivalent to $67.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}  Further eligibility requirements stipulate that:\n*Families must have a female applicant holding a valid ID card\n*An individual applicant must be a widowed or divorced female without male family members\n*Eligible families include those with physically or mentally disabled individuals\n\nFamilies deemed ineligible for cash payments through BISP include those with:{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}\n*Members employed by the Pakistani government, army, or any other government-affiliated agency\n*Members drawing a pension or receiving post-retirement benefits from the government\n*Family members owning more than 3 acres of farmland or more than 80 square yards of residential land\n*Members receiving income from other sources\n*Members holding a machine readable passport\n*Members with a National Identity Card for Overseas citizens\n*Members with a bank account excluding microfinance banks and those catering to low-inc\nome families\n\n==Benefits==\nEligible families receive cash payments of 4834 quarterly.  This amount increases the purchasing power for families earning approximately RS 5,000 each month by 20%.  Most low-income families spend 50\u201370% of total income on food alone.  According to BISP, the cash payment of RS 3,000 every two months, or RS 1,500 each month, will allow a family of 5\u20136 to purchase 20\u201325 days worth of flour.{{Sfn|Handayani-Burkley 2009}}\n\n==Criticism==\nSince the program's inception, critics have pointed out several overall flaws in the Benazir Income Support Program design.  Some claim that the amount of RS 3000 bi-monthly, or RS 1,500 per month, is not enough to move impoverished families above the poverty line as this would require RS 2,550 per month.  Another major flaw with BISP is its lack of conditionality.  Conditional cash transfer programs in Latin America have experienced greater degrees of success because recipient families must meet certain requirements before receiving a cash payment.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}  These programs build human capital through requiring recipients to enroll their children in primary education, participate in health and nutrition seminars, and visit health care providers.{{Sfn|Rawlings-Rubio 2003}}  Apart from the Waseela-e-Taleem initiative, cash payments do not require recipients to meet particular obligations in return for cash payments.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n \nThere have also been accusations of corruption and political favouritism.  By some estimates, only 50\u201360 percent of beneficiaries actually receive cash payments from BISP. The previous method of identifying families through the recommendation of Parliamentarians was flawed.  Many have claimed that Parliamentarians simply recommended their own family and friends to receive cash payments.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}  It has been pointed out that there is a disproportionate number of families receiving BISP aid in geographic areas where the ruling Pakistan People's Party dominates.  For example, in the Prime Minister's hometown of Multan, there is twice the number of people receiving BISP payments than in Lahore, the opposition party's stronghold.  Punjab, another area where opposition parties dominate, has the lowest ratio of eligible families\u20141,974 for every 100,000 people; versus 6,829 families for every 100,000 people in Sindh, the ruling party's stronghold.{{Sfn|Ghauri 2012}}  Beneficiaries have also complained that the postal service charges an additional RS 100 to RS 200 for each delivery of payment.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}\n\nOther critics have argued that as the Benazir Income Support Programme makes up a substantial portion of the Pakistani government's budget, impact evaluations should be conducted to evaluate the benefits and actual need for the program.{{Sfn|Shahzad 2011}}\n\n==List of Chairpersons of Benazir Income Support Program==\n{| class=\"wikitable\n|-\n!align=center|Name of Chairperson\n!align=center|Entered Office\n!align=center|Left Office\n|-\n|[[Farzana Raja]]\n|July 2008\n|March 2013\n|-\n|Vacant\n|March 2013\n|November 2013\n|-\n|[[Enver Baig]]\n|November 2013\n|November 2014\n|-\n|Vacant\n|November 2014\n|February 2015\n|-\n|[[Marvi Memon]]\n|February 2015\n|June 2018\n|-\n|Vacant\n|June 2018\n|October 2018\n|-\n|[[Sania Nishtar]]\n|October 2018\n|Present\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n<!--- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. --->\n* {{Cite web |title=Benazir Income Support Programme |year=2011 |url=http://www.bisp.gov.pk/ |ref={{SfnRef|Benazir Income Support Programme}} }}\n* {{Cite web |last=Ghauri |first=Irfan |date=4 February 2012 |title=Benazir Income Support Programme: Does the Cash Flow to Blue-Eyed Voters? |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/331740/benazir-income-support-programme-does-the-cash-flow-to-blue-eyed-voters/ |ref={{SfnRef|Ghauri 2012}} |display-authors=etal}}\n* {{Cite web |last1=Handayani |first1=Sri Wening |last2=Burkley |first2=Clifford |year=2009 |title=Social Assistance and Conditional Cash Transfers: The Proceedings of the Regional Workshop. |url=http://www.adb.org/publications/social-assistance-and-conditional-cash-transfers-proceedings-regional-workshop |ref={{SfnRef|Handayani-Burkley 2009}} }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Rawlings |first1=Laura B |last2=Rubio |first2=Gloria M. |year=2003 |title=Evaluating the Impact of Conditional Cash Transfer Programs: Lessons from Latin America |ref={{SfnRef|Rawlings-Rubio 2003}} }}\n* {{Cite web |last=Shahzad |first=Farakh |date=25 June 2011 |title=BISP\u2014A Commitment Falling Short \n|url=http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2011/06/25/news/profit/bisp-a-commitment-falling-short/ |ref={{SfnRef|Shahzad 2011}} }}\n* {{Cite web |last=Saddam |first=Khan |date=28 Sep 2017 |title=BISP\n|url=http://www.pakistanblogger.com/bisp-tracking-by-cnic/ |ref={{SfnRef|Shahzad 2011}} }}\n* {{Cite web |last=Saddam |first=Hassan |date=30 Oct 2019 |title=BISP - Dr Sania Nishtar is Chairman in regime of PTI governance.\n|url=http://www.bisp.com.pk |ref={{SfnRef|Shahzad 2011}} }}\n\n[[Category:Welfare in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Government of Yousaf Raza Gillani]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Benazir Bhutto]]\n[[Category:2008 introductions]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Social programs]]\n", "name_user": "45.116.233.43", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Saima)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benazir_Income_Support_Programme"}
{"title_page": "Robert Southey", "text_new": "{{For|the chairman of the Australian Ballet|Robert Southey (businessman)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2018}}<!--numerous paragraphs without citations-->\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox poet\n|name = Robert Southey\n|image = Robert Southey by Vandyke.jpg\n|caption = Portrait, {{circa|1795}}\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1774|08|12|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Bristol]], England\n|death_date = {{death date and age|1843|03|21|1774|08|12|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[London]], England\n|spouse = {{ubl|Edith Fricker (1795\u20131838; her death)|Caroline Anne Bowles (1839\u20131843; his death)}}\n|occupation = Poet, historian, biographer, essayist\n|movement = [[Romanticism]]\n|genre = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Robert Southey''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|a\u028a|\u00f0|i}} or {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u028c|\u00f0|i}};{{efn |Southey's biographer comments that: \"There should be no doubt as to the proper pronunciation of the name: 'Sowthey'. The poet himself complained that people in the North would call him 'Mr Suthy'\" (Jack Simmons: ''Southey'' (London: Collins, 1945), p. 9). Byron rhymed Southey with \"mouthy\" (''Don Juan'' Canto the First, Stanza 205) [http://www.online-literature.com/byron/don-juan/1/ Retrieved 12 August 2012.] The pronunciation criticized by Southey is still used; the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' cites both for the word \"Southeyan\" (relating to Robert Southey or his work).}} 12 August 1774 \u2013 21 March 1843) was an English poet of the [[Romantic poetry|Romantic]] school, one of the [[Lake Poets]] along with [[William Wordsworth]] and [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]], and England's [[Poet Laureate]] for 30 years from 1813 until his death in 1843. Although his fame has been eclipsed by that of Wordsworth and Coleridge, his verse still enjoys some popularity. The English word \"[[zombie]]\", from the [[Haitian French]] \"zombi\", is purported to have first been recorded by Southey in his 1819 essay ''History of Brazil''.\n\n==Achievements==\nSouthey was also a prolific letter writer, literary scholar, essay writer, historian and biographer. His biographies include the life and works of [[John Bunyan]], [[John Wesley]], [[William Cowper]], [[Oliver Cromwell]] and [[Horatio Nelson]]. The last has rarely been out of print since its publication in 1813 and was adapted as the 1926 British film ''[[Nelson (1926 film)|Nelson]]''.\n\nHe was also a renowned scholar of Portuguese and Spanish literature and history, translating a number of works from those two languages into English and writing a ''History of Brazil'' (part of his planned ''History of Portugal'', which he never completed) and a ''History of the Peninsular War''.\n\nPerhaps his most enduring contribution to literary history is the children's classic ''The Story of the Three Bears'', the original [[Goldilocks and the Three Bears|Goldilocks]] story, first published in Southey's prose collection ''The Doctor''. He also wrote on political issues, which led to a brief, non-sitting, spell as a [[Tory Party (UK)|Tory]] Member of Parliament.\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Robert Southey by Sir Francis Chantrey, 1832, National Portrait Gallery, London.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Robert Southey, by Sir [[Francis Chantrey]], 1832, National Gallery, London]]\nRobert Southey was born in Wine Street, [[Bristol]], to Robert Southey and Margaret Hill. He was educated at [[Westminster School]], London (where he was expelled for writing an article in ''The Flagellant'' attributing the invention of flogging to the Devil),<ref>Geoffrey Treasure: ''Who's Who in Late Hanoverian Britain'' (2nd, enlarged edition, London: Shepheard-Walwyn, 1997), p. 143.</ref> and at [[Balliol College]], Oxford.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite web |last=Carnall |first=Geoffrey |title=Southey, Robert (1774\u20131843), poet and reviewer |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/26056 |work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |edition=online |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2004 |accessdate=26 August 2012}} {{ODNBsub}}</ref> Southey later said of Oxford, \"All I learnt was a little swimming... and a little boating.\"\n\nExperimenting with a writing partnership with Samuel Taylor Coleridge, most notably in their joint composition of ''[[The Fall of Robespierre]]'', Southey published his first collection of poems in 1794. The same year, Southey, Coleridge, [[Robert Lovell]] and several others discussed creating an idealistic community (\"[[pantisocracy]]\") on the banks of the [[Susquehanna River]] in America:\n{{quote| Their wants would be simple and natural; their toil need not be such as the slaves of luxury endure; where possessions were held in common, each would work for all; in their cottages the best books would have a place; literature and science, bathed anew in the invigorating stream of life and nature, could not but rise reanimated and purified. Each young man should take to himself a mild and lovely woman for his wife; it would be her part to prepare their innocent food, and tend their hardy and beautiful race.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>}}\n\nSouthey was the first to reject the idea as unworkable, suggesting that they move the intended location to [[Wales]], but when they failed to agree, the plan was abandoned.\n\nIn 1799 Southey and Coleridge were involved with early experiments with [[nitrous oxide]] (laughing gas), conducted by the [[Cornish people|Cornish]] scientist [[Humphry Davy]].<ref>[http://www.nndb.com/people/028/000083776/ Humphry Davy], NNDB</ref>\n\n[[File:Illustrirte Zeitung (1843) 06 016 2 Southey's Haus, Gretahof.PNG|thumb|[[Greta Hall]], [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]]]][[File:Matilda Betham, Portrait of Edith May Southey, 1809.jpg|thumb|left|Mary Matilda Betham, ''Portrait of Edith May Southey,'' 1809{{r|Letter 1669}}]][[File:Matilda Betham, Portrait of Herbert Southey, 1809.jpg|thumb|left|[[Mary Matilda Betham]], ''Portrait of Herbert,'' 1809<ref name=\"Letter 1669\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rc.umd.edu/editions/southey_letters/Part_Three/HTML/letterEEd.26.1669.html |title=Letter 1669. Robert Southey to Grosvenor Charles Bedford, 12 August 1809 | work=The Collected Letters of Robert Southey |publisher=Romantic Circles, University of Maryland |date=12 August 1809 |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref>]]\nSouthey married Edith Fricker, Coleridge's sister-in-law, at [[St. Mary Redcliffe]], [[Bristol]], on 14 November 1795. The Southeys made their home at [[Greta Hall]], [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]], in the [[Lake District]], living on his tiny income. Also living at Greta Hall and supported by him were Sara Coleridge and her three children (after Coleridge abandoned them) and the widow of poet [[Robert Lovell]] and her son.\n\nIn 1808 Southey met [[Walter Savage Landor]], whose work he admired, and they became close friends. That same year he wrote ''Letters from England'' under the pseudonym Don Manuel Alvarez Espriella, an account of a tour supposedly from a foreigner's viewpoint. Through the mouth of his pseudonym Southey is critical of the disparity between the haves and have-nots in English society, arguing that a change in taxation policy would be needed to foster a greater degree of equity.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\nFrom 1809 Southey contributed to the ''[[Quarterly Review]]''. He had become so well known by 1813 that he was appointed [[Poet Laureate]] after [[Walter Scott]] refused the post.\n\nIn 1819, through a mutual friend ([[John Rickman]]), Southey met the leading [[civil engineer]] [[Thomas Telford]] and struck up a friendship. From mid-August to 1 October 1819, Southey accompanied Telford on an extensive tour of his engineering projects in the [[Scottish Highlands]], keeping a diary of his observations. This was published in 1929 as ''Journal of a Tour in Scotland in 1819''. He was also a friend of the Dutch poet [[Willem Bilderdijk]], whom he met twice, in 1824 and 1826, at Bilderdijk's home in [[Leiden]]. He expressed appreciation of the work of the English novelist [[Ann Doherty]].<ref>Links to letters [[Romantic Circles]]: \"Attersoll, Ann...\" [https://www.rc.umd.edu/node/103426 Retrieved 11 November 2017.]</ref>\n\nIn 1837 Southey received a letter from [[Charlotte Bront\u00eb]], seeking his advice on some of her poems. He wrote back praising her talents, but discouraging her from writing professionally: \"Literature cannot be the business of a woman's life,\" he argued. Years later, Bront\u00eb remarked to a friend that the letter was \"kind and admirable; a little stringent, but it did me good.\"\n\nIn 1838 Edith died and Southey remarried, to [[Caroline Anne Southey|Caroline Anne Bowles]], also a poet, on 4 June 1839.<ref>{{cite web |last= Blain |first=Virginia H. |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/26054 |title=Southey, Caroline Anne Bowles (1786\u20131854), poet and writer |work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |edition=online |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2004 |accessdate=}} {{ODNBsub}}</ref> Southey's mind was giving way when he wrote a last letter to his friend Landor in 1839, but he continued to mention Landor's name when generally incapable of mentioning any one. He died on 21 March 1843 and was buried in the churchyard of [[Crosthwaite Parish Church|Crosthwaite Church]], Keswick, where he had worshipped for forty years. There is a memorial to him inside the church, with an epitaph written by his friend, William Wordsworth.\n\nA few of Southey's ballads are still read by British schoolchildren, the best-known being ''[[The Inchcape Rock]]'', ''God's Judgement on a Wicked Bishop'', ''[[After Blenheim]]'' (possibly one of the earliest anti-war poems) and ''[[Cataract of Lodore]]''.\n\nAs a prolific writer and commentator, Southey introduced or popularised a number of words into the English language. The term ''autobiography'', for example, was used by Southey in 1809 in the ''Quarterly Review'', in which he predicted an \"epidemical rage for autobiography\", which indeed has continued to the present day.{{efn|The ''Oxford English Dictionary'' entry for ''autobiography'' contains an earlier quotation using this word.}}\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Knife-Grinder-Gillray.jpeg|thumb|A 1797 caricature of Southey's early radical poetry]]\nAlthough originally a radical supporter of the [[French Revolution]], Southey followed the trajectory of his fellow Romantic poets Wordsworth and Coleridge towards conservatism. Embraced by the Tory establishment as Poet Laureate, and from 1807 in receipt of a yearly stipend from them, he vigorously supported the [[Robert Jenkinson, 2nd Earl of Liverpool|Liverpool]] government. He argued against parliamentary reform (\"the railroad to ruin with the Devil for driver\"), blamed the [[Peterloo Massacre]] on an allegedly revolutionary \"rabble\" killed and injured by government troops, and spurned Catholic emancipation.<ref>{{cite ODNB |id=26056 |title=Southey, Robert (1774\u20131843) |last1=Carnall |first1=Geoffrey}}</ref> In 1817 he privately proposed [[penal transportation]] for those guilty of \"libel\" or \"sedition\". He had in mind figures like [[Thomas Jonathan Wooler]] and [[William Hone]], whose prosecution he urged. Such writers were guilty, he wrote in the ''Quarterly Review'', of \"inflaming the turbulent temper of the manufacturer and disturbing the quiet attachment of the peasant to those institutions under which he and his fathers have dwelt in peace.\" Wooler and Hone were acquitted, but the threats caused another target, [[William Cobbett]], to emigrate temporarily to the United States.\n\nIn some respects, Southey was ahead of his time in his views on social reform. For example, he was an early critic of the evils the new factory system brought to early 19th-century Britain. He was appalled by the living conditions in towns like [[Birmingham]] and [[Manchester]] and especially by employment of children in factories and outspoken about them. He sympathised with the pioneering socialist plans of [[Robert Owen]], advocated that the state promote public works to maintain high employment, and called for universal education.<ref>Carnall (1971), p. 9.</ref>\n\nGiven his departure from radicalism, and his attempts to have former fellow travellers prosecuted, it is unsurprising that less successful contemporaries who kept the faith attacked Southey. They saw him as selling out for money and respectability.\n\nIn 1817 Southey was confronted with the surreptitious publication of a radical play, ''Wat Tyler'', which he had written in 1794 at the height of his radical period. This was instigated by his enemies in an attempt to embarrass the Poet Laureate and highlight his apostasy from radical poet to supporter of the Tory establishment. One of his most savage critics was [[William Hazlitt]]. In his portrait of Southey, in ''[[The Spirit of the Age]]'', he wrote: \"He wooed Liberty as a youthful lover, but it was perhaps more as a mistress than a bride; and he has since wedded with an elderly and not very reputable lady, called Legitimacy.\" Southey largely ignored his critics but was forced to defend himself when William Smith, a member of Parliament, rose in the House of Commons on 14 March to attack him. In a spirited response Southey wrote an open letter to the MP, in which he explained that he had always aimed at lessening human misery and bettering the condition of all the lower classes and that he had only changed in respect of \"the means by which that amelioration was to be effected.\"<ref name=\"Speck 2006, p. 172\">Speck (2006) p. 172.</ref> As he put it, \"that as he learnt to understand the institutions of his country, he learnt to appreciate them rightly, to love, and to revere, and to defend them.\"<ref name=\"Speck 2006, p. 172\"/>\n\nAnother critic of Southey in his later period was [[Thomas Love Peacock]], who scorned him in the character of Mr. Feathernest in his 1817 satirical novel ''[[Melincourt (novel)|Melincourt]]''.<ref>Howard Mills: ''Peacock, His Circle and His Age'' (Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University Press, 1969) p. 115 ff. [https://books.google.com/books?id=9C9mkMwfyYMC&pg=PA115&lpg=PA115&dq=Peacock+Mr.+Feathernest&source=bl&ots=pNxwgzv2D6&sig=LF3p3d6E0iZOrEAh4b1NE_Tu944&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi7g_ann8ncAhUFkiwKHb9JAX4Q6AEwAHoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=Peacock%20Mr.%20Feathernest&f=false Retrieved 31 July 2018.](</ref>\n\nHe was often mocked for what were seen as sycophantic odes to the king, notably in [[Lord Byron|Byron]]'s long ironic dedication of ''[[Don Juan (poem)|Don Juan]]'' to Southey. In the poem Southey is dismissed as insolent, narrow and shabby. This was based both on Byron's disrespect for Southey's literary talent, and his disdain for what he perceived as Southey's hypocritical turn to conservatism later in life. Much of the animosity between the two men can be traced back to Byron's belief that Southey had spread rumours about him and [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]] being in a \"League of Incest\" during their time on [[Lake Geneva]] in 1816, an accusation that Southey strenuously denied.\n\nIn response, Southey attacked what he called the [[Satanic School]] among modern poets in the preface to his poem, ''A Vision of Judgement'', written after the death of [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]]. While not naming Byron, it was clearly directed at him. Byron retaliated with ''[[The Vision of Judgment]]'', a parody of Southey's poem.\n\nWithout his prior knowledge, the [[Jacob Pleydell-Bouverie, 2nd Earl of Radnor|Earl of Radnor]], an admirer of his work, had Southey returned as MP for the latter's [[pocket borough]] seat of [[Downton (UK Parliament constituency)|Downton]] in [[Wiltshire]] at the [[1826 United Kingdom general election|1826 general election]], as an opponent of Catholic emancipation, but Southey refused to sit, causing a by-election in December that year, pleading that he did not have a large enough estate to support him through political life,<ref>MPs were then unsalaried, and expected to treat voters at election times.</ref> or want to take on the hours full attendance required. He wished to continue living in the Lake District and preferred to defend the [[Church of England]] in writing rather than speech. He declared that \"for me to change my scheme of life and go into Parliament, would be to commit a moral and intellectual suicide.\" His friend John Rickman, a Commons clerk, noted that \"prudential reasons would forbid his appearing in London\" as a Member.<ref name=hop>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1820-1832/member/southey-robert-1774-1843] History of Parliament article.</ref>\n\nIn 1835 Southey declined the offer of a [[baronet]]cy, but accepted a life pension of \u00a3300 a year from Prime Minister [[Sir Robert Peel, 2nd Baronet|Sir Robert Peel]].<ref name=hop/> He is buried in the churchyard of [[Crosthwaite Parish Church]] in [[Cumbria]].\n\n==Honours and memberships==\nSouthey was elected a member of the [[American Antiquarian Society]] in 1822.<ref>[http://www.americanantiquarian.org/memberlists American Antiquarian Society Members Directory]</ref> He was also a member of the [[Royal Spanish Academy]].\n\n==A partial list of works==\n*''Harold, or, The Castle of Morford'' (an unpublished Robin Hood novel that Southey wrote in 1791).<ref>Bodleian MS. Eng. Misc. e. 121</ref>\n*''[[The Fall of Robespierre]]'' (1794) (with [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]])\n*''Poems:containing the Retrospect, Odes, Elegies, Sonnets, &c.'' (with [[Robert Lovell]])\n*''[[Joan of Arc (poem)|Joan of Arc]]'' (1796)\n*''Icelandic Poetry, or The Edda of S\u00e6mund'' (1797)\n*[https://books.google.com/books/about/Poems_1797.html?id=6WBbAAAAMAAJ ''Poems'' (1797\u20131799)]\n*[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/007673101 ''Letters Written During a Short Residence in Spain and Portugal'' (1797)]\n*[http://literaryballadarchive.com/PDF/Southey_16_St-Patrick_s_Purgatory.pdf ''St. Patrick's Purgatory'' (1798)]\n*''[[After Blenheim]]'' (1798)\n*[http://www.rc.umd.edu/editions/shelley/devil/devil.stc1799.htm ''The Devil's Thoughts'' (1799)]. Revised ed. pub. in 1827 as \"The Devil's Walk\". (with Samuel Taylor Coleridge)\n*[http://spenserians.cath.vt.edu/TextRecord.php?&action=GET&textsid=35422 ''English Eclogues'' (1799)]\n*[http://www.poetryfoundation.org/poem/174448 ''The Old Man's Comforts and How He Gained Them'' (1799)]\n*''[[Thalaba the Destroyer]]'' (1801)\n*''[[The Inchcape Rock]]'' (1802)\n*''[[Madoc (poem)|Madoc]]'' (1805)\n*[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100731164 ''Letters from England: By Don Manuel Alvarez Espriella'' (1807)], the observations of a fictitious Spaniard.\n*[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/007703527 ''Chronicle of the Cid, from the Spanish'' (1808)]\n*''[[Curse of Kehama|The Curse of Kehama]]'' (1810)\n*[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/009270236 ''History of Brazil'' (3 vols.) (1810\u20131819)]<ref>{{cite journal |title=Review of ''History of Brazil'' by Robert Southey. Part the First |journal=The Quarterly Review |date=November 1810 |volume=4 |pages=451\u2013474 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.$b661431;view=1up;seq=466}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Review of ''History of Brazil'' by Robert Southey, vol. ii |journal=The Quarterly Review |date=October 1817 |volume=18 |pages=99\u2013128 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044092624956;view=1up;seq=109}}</ref>\n*[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/009357471?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Southey%2C%20Robert%2C%201774-1843.%22 ''The Life of Horatio, Lord Viscount Nelson'' (1813)]\n*''[[Roderick the Last of the Goths]]'' (1814)\n*[https://archive.org/details/journaloftourinn01sout/page/n10/mode/2up ''Journal of a tour in the Netherlands in the autumn of 1815'' (1902)]\n*''Sir [[Thomas Malory]]'s Le Morte D'Arthur'' (1817)\n*[https://archive.org/details/wattylerdramatic01sout ''Wat Tyler: A Dramatic Poem'' (1817; written in 1794)]\n*''[[Cataract of Lodore]]'' (1820)\n*[https://archive.org/details/lifewesleyandri01soutgoog ''The Life of Wesley; and Rise and Progress of Methodism'' (2 vols.) (1820)]\n*''[[What Are Little Boys Made Of?]]'' (1820)\n*[[iarchive:visionofjudgemen00sout|''A Vision of Judgement'' (1821)]]\n*[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/008687988 ''History of the Peninsular War, 1807\u20131814'' (3 vols.) (1823\u20131832)]\n*[http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/4243 ''Sir Thomas More; or, Colloquies on the Progress and Prospects of Society'' (1829)]\n*[https://archive.org/details/workswilliamcow12cowpgoog ''The Works of William Cowper'', 15 vols., ed. (1833\u20131837)]\n*[https://archive.org/details/englishseamenhow00soutiala ''Lives of the British Admirals, with an Introductory View of the Naval History of England'' (5 vols.) (1833\u201340)]; republished as \"English Seamen\" in 1895.\n*[http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/webbin/book/lookupname?key=Southey%2C%20Robert%2C%201774-1843 ''The Doctor'' (7 vols.) (1834\u20131847)]. Includes [[Goldilocks and the Three Bears|The Story of the Three Bears]] (1837).\n*[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/008884719 The Poetical Works of Robert Southey, Collected by Himself (1837)]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry}}\n*''[[Recollections of the Lake Poets]]''\n*[[Goldilocks and the Three Bears]]\n*[[Lake Poets]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Carnall, Geoffrey, ''Writers and Their Works: Robert Southey'', (Longman Group: London 1971)\n*Curry, Kenneth (ed.), ''New Letters of Robert Southey'', 2 vols (Columbia UP: New York and London, 1965)\n*Dowden, Edward (ed.), ''The Correspondence of Robert Southey with Caroline Bowles'' (Dublin and London, 1881)\n*Low, Dennis, ''The Literary Prot\u00e9g\u00e9es of the Lake Poets'' (Aldershot: Ashgate, 2006)\n*Madden, John Lionel, ''Robert Southey: the critical heritage'' (London: Routledge & Kegan Paul, 1972)\n*Pratt, Lynda, ed. ''Robert Southey, Poetical Works, 1793\u20131810'', 5 vols. (London: Pickering and Chatto, 2004)\n*Simmons, Jack, ''Southey'', (Kennikat: Washington, 1945)\n*Southey, Charles Cuthbert (ed.), ''The Life and Correspondence of Robert Southey'' (New York, 1855).\n*Speck, W. A. ''Robert Southey: Entire Man of Letters'', (Yale University Press, 2006)\n*{{cite book |last=Stephen |first=Leslie |authorlink=Leslie Stephen |title=Studies of a Biographer |year=1902 |publisher=Duckworth and Co. |location=London |pages=45\u201385 |chapter=[[s:Studies of a Biographer/Southey's Letters|Southey's Letters]]}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n*{{Gutenberg author |id=Southey,+Robert | name=Robert Southey}}\n*{{Internet Archive author |sname=Robert Southey}}\n*{{Librivox author |id=595}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070703000642/http://www.pricejb.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Southey.PDF The Pilgrim To Compostella]\n*[http://www.edsanders.com/stories/3bears/3bears.htm The original Southey version of The Three Bears]\n*[http://digital.library.wisc.edu/1711.dl/Literature.Southey The Robert Southey Collection]: Presented online by [http://uwdc.library.wisc.edu The University of Wisconsin Digital Collections Center]. Titles include:\n**[http://digital.library.wisc.edu/1711.dl/Literature.RSouthey1 Southey, Robert, 1774\u20131843. Southey's Common-place book. First series. Choice passages. Collections for English manners and literature: 2d. ed. (1850)]\n**[http://digital.library.wisc.edu/1711.dl/Literature.RSouthey2 Southey, Robert, 1774\u20131843. Southey's Common-place book. Second series. Special collections: 2d. ed. (1850])\n**[http://digital.library.wisc.edu/1711.dl/Literature.RSouthey3 Southey, Robert, 1774\u20131843. Southey's Common-place book. Third series. Analytical readings: 2d. ed. (1850)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130527233026/http://tehnikaa.ru/arh26/history.pdf History of Brazil] Southey, Robert\n**[http://digital.library.wisc.edu/1711.dl/Litera